Solution:
We start by listing the 15 coin tosses as a sequence of H's and T's. Let $H_n$ denote the position of the $n$th head in the sequence, and let $T_n$ denote the position of the $n$th tail. Then we have the following diagram:

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw((-1,0)--(16,0));
label("$H_1$", (1,0), S);
label("$H_2$", (2,0), S);
label("$T_1$", (3,0), S);
label("$H_3$", (4,0), S);
label("$T_2$", (5,0), S);
label("$H_4$", (6,0), S);
label("$T_3$", (7,0), S);
label("$T_4$", (8,0), S);
label("$H_5$", (9,0), S);
label("$T_5$", (10,0), S);
label("$T_6$", (11,0), S);
label("$H_6$", (12,0), S);
label("$T_7$", (13,0), S);
label("$T_8$", (14,0), S);
label("$H_7$", (15,0), S);

fill((1,0.5)--(2,0.5)--(2,-0.5)--(1,-0.5)--cycle, gray(0.7));
fill((4,0.5)--(5,0.5)--(5,-0.5)--(4,-0.5)--cycle, gray(0.7));
fill((6,0.5)--(7,0.5)--(7,-0.5)--(6,-0.5)--cycle, gray(0.7));
fill((9,0.5)--(10,0.5)--(10,-0.5)--(9,-0.5)--cycle, gray(0.7));

draw((1,-0.5)--(15,-0.5),dashed);
draw((1,0.5)--(15,0.5));
[/asy]

The four shaded regions represent the two HH, three HT, four TH, and five TT subsequences. Thus, we must choose the positions of the $H_n$ and $T_n$ in the diagram so that they fall within the appropriate regions. There are $\binom{15}{2}$ ways to choose the positions of the HH, $\binom{13}{3}$ ways to choose the positions of the HT, $\binom{9}{4}$ ways to choose the positions of the TH, and $\binom{5}{5}$ ways to choose the positions of the TT. Thus, the total number of valid sequences is
\[\binom{15}{2} \cdot \binom{13}{3} \cdot \binom{9}{4} \cdot \binom{5}{5} = \frac{15!}{2!3!4!5!} = \boxed{2522520}.\]

Solution:
Any subset of three or more points uniquely determines a convex polygon.  There are $\binom{10}{n}$ ways to choose a subset of $n$ points.  However, we must subtract the cases where the vertices are collinear.  The number of collinear triples is simply 10 times the number of subsets of 3 points, minus twice the number of subsets of 4 points, plus twice the number of subsets of 5 points, minus the number of subsets of 6 points.  This gives us a total of:

\begin{align*}
\binom{10}{3} - 10\binom{6}{3} + 2\binom{5}{3} + 2\binom{4}{3} - \binom{3}{3} &= 120 - 10(20) + 2(10) + 2(4) - 1\\
&= \boxed{71}
\end{align*}distinct convex polygons.

